article.description:
The Houston Comets kept their playoffs hopes
alive with a 70-59 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Tuesday
night.
article.headline: Houston ends four-game slide
article.linkText: Comets beat Lynx for first time in four meetings
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- A loss on Tuesday night would have kept the
Houston Comets from making the playoffs for the first time in
franchise history.

But the Minnesota Lynx couldn't eliminate the four-time
champions who had not won a game since July 31.

The Comets kept their playoffs hopes alive with a 70-59 victory
Tuesday night over the Lynx.

Tina Thompson scored 27 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 15 for
Houston (13-18), which ended a four-game losing streak and beat the
Lynx for the first time in four meetings.

Octavia Blue scored a season-high 10 points for the Comets, who
had not won since returning from the month-long Olympic break.

"This was just a really big win for us tonight," Comets coach
Van Chancellor said. "Octavia Blue really played well for us
tonight and sparked this team. She played well defensively and only
had one turnover and gave us a lot of energy."

The Comets must win their three remaining games and get help
from Sacramento and Phoenix to avoid missing the playoffs.

"Hopefully we can keep this going," Thompson said. "I've
believed in us from the beginning. This team can really do some
positive things and that is why I don't think we've given up. We
haven't wavered."

Nicole Ohlde scored 15 points for Minnesota (17-15), which lost
for the fourth time in five games since winning at Houston on Sept.
1. The Lynx still lead the Comets by three games in the Western
Conference.

"Thompson was a huge factor for them tonight," Minnesota coach
Susie McConnell-Serio said. "She was a difference maker. They
capitalized on every opportunity and played desperate and hungry.

"They made a change defensively and we couldn't answer. We're a
team of balance and we didn't get that tonight."

The Lynx got within 56-49 as Ohlde hit a 16-foot jumper with
7:04 left in the game. But Houston responded with a 9-2 run to take
its biggest lead of the game, 65-51, with 4:39 to go.

Dominique Canty scored four points during the run and finished
with 12. Houston used a 21-6 run over the last 9:34 of the first
half to take a 32-26 lead.

"Tonight looked like the old Comets defense," Chancellor
added. "That looked like the kind of Comets defense where we
guarded somebody. We did a really good job all night of getting
them out of what they wanted to do."

Houston used a 21-6 run in the last 9:34 of the first half to
take a 32-26 lead at the break.

Thompson led all scorers with 15-first half points including a
long 3-pointer that gave the Comets a 29-26 lead with 43 seconds
left in the half.

Svetlana Abrosimova led the Lynx with 8 points, scoring each of
them in a 12-0 run that gave Minnesota a 16-7 lead with 13:39 left.
